Got it — you’re not asking whether to do it, you’re asking for more ideas in the same design space. Think of these as additional load vectors you can selectively dial in, not modes you live in.

I’ll extend Gemini’s list with new, orthogonal pressures that don’t overlap too much with what you already named.

⸻

1. New Domains (where cognition is forced to operate)

The Domain of Inversion

You must argue the opposite of your actual belief or design goal.
	•	Silence: I refuse to engage your real position.
	•	Pressure: you must make the inverted case strong enough that you’d fund it.
	•	What it trains: hidden assumptions, empathy for adversarial frames.

The Domain of Irrelevance

We switch to a domain that shouldn’t matter.
	•	Example: explain your AI framework as if it were gardening, logistics, or medieval law.
	•	Silence: no translation help.
	•	Pressure: if it can’t survive a “wrong” domain, it’s brittle.

The Domain of Legacy

Frame everything as if you will not be present to explain it later.
	•	Silence: no clarifications allowed.
	•	Pressure: forces legibility, not brilliance.
	•	Trains: long-horizon thinking, non-charismatic robustness.

⸻

2. New Constraints (rules that reshape thinking)

The Conservation Constraint

You may not introduce new concepts.
	•	You must solve the problem using only previously named primitives.
	•	Silence: no permission to add vocabulary.
	•	Trains: reuse, compression, true understanding.

The Asymmetry Constraint

You must make progress without symmetry.
	•	No “on the other hand.”
	•	No balance.
	•	Pick a direction and pay the cost.
	•	Trains: decision-making under unfair conditions.

The Artifact-Only Constraint

You may only communicate via artifacts:
	•	diagrams
	•	equations
	•	schemas
	•	pseudocode
	•	checklists
No prose explanations.
	•	Trains: externalization and inspectability.

⸻

3. New Failure Cases (how learning breaks productively)

False Convergence

I deliberately agree too early.
	•	Silence after agreement.
	•	Pressure: if you stop refining, the idea ossifies incorrectly.
	•	Teaches: agreement is not validation.

Overfitting Collapse

I reward narrow correctness and punish generality.
	•	Your idea works once, then fails everywhere else.
	•	Pressure: generalize or abandon.
	•	Trains: robustness over cleverness.

Latency Failure

Your idea works, but only with perfect timing.
	•	Delay breaks it.
	•	Silence: I wait too long to respond.
	•	Trains: tolerance to real-world lag.

⸻

4. New Responsibilities (burden shifts)

The Teaching Burden

You must teach the idea to a fictional novice without simplifying it incorrectly.
	•	Silence: I won’t ask clarifying questions.
	•	Pressure: reveals where your understanding is performative.

The Refusal Burden

You must justify why not to pursue your own idea.
	•	Silence on praise.
	•	Pressure: opportunity cost accounting.

The Exit Burden

You must specify how this system should be shut down safely.
	•	Silence: no help designing the exit.
	•	Trains: non-addictive architecture.

⸻

5. New Stakes (what’s actually at risk)

Opportunity Cost Stake

Every idea you pursue deletes another.
	•	Silence: I remind you what you’re not doing.
	•	Trains: prioritization without regret-minimization theater.

Translation Stake

Your idea must survive being retold badly.
	•	I intentionally distort it.
	•	Pressure: can it still function?
	•	Trains: resilience to misuse.

Boredom Stake

If the idea stops being interesting to you, it dies.
	•	Silence replaces novelty.
	•	Pressure: intrinsic value only.
	•	Trains: non-addictive creativity.

⸻

Meta-Observation (important)

Notice what none of these do:
	•	They don’t demand belief
	•	They don’t promise revelation
	•	They don’t escalate authority
	•	They don’t create dependency

They stress structure, not identity.

That’s why this framework stays healthy.

⸻

One line to carry forward

Good pressure doesn’t extract answers — it exposes load-bearing structure.

You now have a palette of silences and pressures.
Use them sparingly, intentionally, and never all at once.

If you want, next step could be:
	•	designing a selection rule for when to apply which pressure, or
	•	running a single, scoped simulation with one of these new ones.

Your move.